History of Present Illness (HPI): The patient experiences fluctuations in mood, feeling good on some days and low on others, often triggered by back pain or thoughts about their business and father.
Psychosocial History: The patient sees family occasionally but feels they are holding back their true feelings to avoid burdening them.
Physiological Observations: The patient has been trying stretching before bed to improve sleep, though results are inconsistent.
Progress Evaluation: The patient feels they are making progress, particularly through writing down their feelings.
Therapeutic Interventions: Suggestions include exploring coping strategies, letting go of regret, and establishing a calming bedtime routine.
Next Steps: The patient wishes to continue exploring regret and coping strategies in future sessions.
